segments.text: Frank suggested that I go back and tell Frank Gould that we would do it his way.
Do it Frank Gould's way?
Yes.
And it was Frank Gould that was the one who was first saying, don't use Webster.
Right.
And then Frank Wardlaw.
The standard botanical practice was to run the words of the name together, like buffalo grass is all one word.
And I insisted on breaking it into two words, because buffalo grass doesn't make much sense.
Well, it does to the botanists.
And so Frank Gould won the day on that one.
I still think it looks funny every time I see those books, but who am I to insist that they change a whole range of literature.
But I remember one of the things I said to Frank Gould, and I wish I could take it back now, he was really a great guy.
And he must have gone home and laughed about it until he was sick, but I told him I didn't want to contribute to the Germanification of the English language.
Cocky kid, I guess.
As you're getting started here, what was your normal work schedule
by the day and by the week.
You got to, normally you got to the campus about what time and did what?
Oh, yeah.
Well, we worked from 8 to 5.
Did you walk or drive?
I drove.
I lived over on Southwest Parkway in apartments over there.
And so I drove.
And parked?
We parked
We had some parking places right by the press there.
There was a parking lot behind the building.
And actually, it was on the street side of the building, but toward the rear.
And then there was a parking garage, which the press used as the shipping room and the warehouse.
That's where all the books were kept and shipped out from.
But there was a little parking there, and I can't remember if I, I think though my parking was on the street.
I think I had just the random street parking for many years.
All right, was there a coffee pot at the Brass?
Yeah.
You know, we were right behind Sabisa, so we could also go over there sometimes for breaks, and then we were right across
just a few hundred feet from campus corner, so we'd go down there.
We used to go after work, we'd go to the Dixie Chicken or one of the other places down there and have a few beers.
But we kind of grew out of that, I guess.
Right, and then lunch would be where?
Oh, I usually went home for lunch, had lunch at home with my wife, and then check the mail and then get back to work.
And you never had to worry about your car being broken in?
Oh, no, certainly not.
The worst thing that ever happened was that one time I parked there and there was a fellow mowing the grass.
I didn't pay much attention to it.
When I came back out either for lunch or after work,
Apparently his mower had hit a piece of rebar that was in the grass.
It had gone right through the side window of my car.
But I went to the university and told them about it, and they paid for it.
No problem, no questions asked.
And did the press staff do some things together?
Yeah, we used to have...
Really nice receptions for authors in the Wardlaw's residence.
Frank and Rosemary's residence was
only the second place on campus where liquor was allowed to be served.
Can you describe how that came about?
Well, I wasn't here then, of course, but I understand that that was one of the conditions that Frank put up on coming to Texas A&M, that he wanted to have a place.
I mean, if he was going to live on campus, he wanted to be able to entertain guests and authors and have that kind of...
reception for new books and new authors.
That was one of the conditions he put on it, and apparently it was approved.
I assume that the Board of Regents had to approve that, but I don't know the story really.
Let me add to this a little bit of my own experience that I think might fit here.
I was

fairly new on the job as dean of faculties, and I got a call one Monday morning from Dr. Jack Williams, our president, telling me to stop what I was doing and to go over to the new Holiday Inn and pick up Frank and Rosemary Wardlaw and give them a tour of the campus.
I said, oh, they're visiting here.
And he said, well, he's the new director of the press.
I said, press?
How long have we had a press?
He said, since yesterday afternoon when John and Sarah Lindsay got me and Margaret and Frank and Rosemary together.
And he said, and you're the chairman of the Press Advisor Committee.
And I said, oh, who's on the committee?
And he said, you tell me who you want on there.
But then he said, your job is to tour him around the campus.
We've got to find a place to put the press.
It had been recommended that it be located in that maroon and white building.
Reed McDonald.
In the Reed McDonald building.
which I and others thought was among the least attractive buildings on the campus and the suggestion was the basement, the ground level, below ground level.

We walked through it and Frank was noticeably turned off and I shared that opinion and we were driving elsewhere on the campus looking around and as we passed that big old board house he asked what it was.

And I told him that that was the building where the board of, then board of directors, I don't know whether now they're regents, where they stayed when they came to their meeting and that they had new quarters over in the new wing of the Memorial Student Center and it was vacant.
Well, he was much taken by that and I understand that he then
broached the subject with Dr. Williams about putting the press there and he and Rosemary live downstairs and the press be upstairs.
So as far as I know that's how that came to be and I had never heard of any other competitor for that
place, so it was a very fine use for a pleasant old structure.
Describe some of those Wardlaw-hosted social events for authors and others.
They were wonderful.
We had people in from all over Texas for those things, and of course Frank had been
in Texas for 25 years or before, so he had lots of friends from around the state.
We had people from like John Henry Falk and Mrs. Dobie used to come all the time to those receptions and parties.
Well, she was also the former Mrs. Webb, I believe, right?
Isn't she the one who was married to both men?
No, no, no, no.
She was Webb's widow and had been married to former Mayor and Congressman Maury Maverick.
That's it, Maverick.
That's right, you're right.
No, I don't.
Frank always called her the double-barreled widow.
And as I recall, she always smiled over it.
Yeah.
And the folklore fiction writer from over in the Big Thicket?
Bill Brett.
Bill Brett.
Yeah, now Bill didn't come along until 77, I think it was.
He came in with his stories, or sent Frank those stories.
and asked if we'd be interested.
And stolen steers was the first thing he sent.
Frank, I remember we all were talking about that.
Frank said, I received this from this fellow over in the Big Thicket.
He doesn't have any credentials, no education much, but it's a wonderful story.
And he asked Margaret and me to read it and tell him what we thought.
And we thought it was great, too, so we published it.
And it was one of the best things we ever did, I think.
Describe Mr. Brett.
Old Bill was just an East Texas cowboy.
He always said that he had been a postmaster and cowboy and oil hand and anything it took to raise a family.
Was he a pleasant author to deal with, to work with?
Oh, yeah.
He had no preconceptions about what publishing should be or how he should be treated by

the publisher and he just he came to us just as he dealt with anybody else in his life you know very straightforward and he's still he's still living he's we're in liberty county and understand his health's not too good so
I think it'd be great for somebody to get his story before he's gone.
As you are getting settled in as an editor, what were some of your learning experiences?
Well, I told you about that one with Frank Gould.
That was definitely a learning experience.
I also learned a little bit more about Frank Wardlaw.
type of manager he was.
And I had promised Frank that I would stay for five years, because he didn't want to have to replace me sooner than that.
He just wanted some continuity.
And so I promised him that I would stay at the press for five years.
So after I'd been here for a couple of years, I found out that he was planning to retire in 78.
So he was going to be leaving sooner than I was.
And also found that after a couple of tries that he wanted me to do my job, my part of the team, and that he appreciated my suggestions for acquisitions.
But unless it was something that really caught his attention, it probably was not going to be encouraged.
Frank was...
I don't know if there's a word for it.
I can't think of a word for it.
He was an autocrat, but one in a very nice way.
He ran the operation.
He ran the show.
And that was that.
If you weren't hired to be the associate director of the press,
He really didn't expect any input from you in that regard.
You were hired to do your job and you did it.
But he was a wonderfully congenial manager and always was able to talk to people and encourage them and make them feel like they were the most important person at the press.
he had a wonderful way with people.
Can you remember some examples of his sense of humor?
Oh yeah, but I can't repeat those for recording.
One of the most memorable stories he ever told me was just had to do with
Wreck of a Circus Train.
I really shouldn't repeat that one on tape.
Wreck of a Circus Train.
This was before you came to A&M, or after?
This was just a funny story he told.
Oh, just a funny story.
It was one night after one of those parties.
As I was leaving, he told me... And the parties quite often lasted how long?
To what hours?
Oh, well...
You know, if it was just the bunch of us, just the press crew, it could go on into the wee hours of the morning.
Generally, though, if it was an official reception or press autographing or just a party to honor one of the authors, it would usually break up fairly early, midnight, 1 o'clock.
Don't I remember John Henry Falk
being one of the people able to go on hour after hour after hour.
Oh, yes.
Yeah.
And one party was at Margaret Ingram's house, and John Henry Falk and Bill Brett were both there.
And they started trading stories, and that did go on for hours.
But it was just fascinating.
Fascinating to hear them
trading stories with each other.
As you worked for Frank, did you become aware of any no-no's?
That no, this will not, he will not approve this or that or something?
Oh, yeah.
He had a very strong sense of what Texans wanted to read.
and what they would not tolerate in their books.
And we turned down a couple of books that had
included stories that he felt were not something that the Texas audience for regional books would tolerate.
What were those?
One of them was... Well, what were those guidelines?
Well, the guidelines were just the kind of language that was used in the book.
That the language was too strong?
Right, right.
Four-letter words were out.
And Dirty Stories were definitely out.
One of those books was published by the University of Illinois Press just before I left there.
It was one that Frank had turned down at the University of Texas Press.
But it ended up at Illinois, and Illinois had no problem with it.
And the title of it was Pissing in the Snow, Another Ozark Folk Tales.
that that was one that Frank turned down because he didn't think that the market for Texas books would support a book like that.
And in fact, he thought that there would be a negative reaction to a book with a title like that and those kinds of stories in it.
What do you think were his favorite topics, favorite subject areas generally?
Oh, I think, of course, the art books he loved.
He loved to publish art.
He loved art.
They had beautiful art throughout their apartment.
And on every wall, you'd see these paintings by Texas artists that were just fabulous.
And so I think the opportunity to come here to Texas A&M

and the connection with joe and betty moore who funded the start of the texas art series i think it was just perfect it was serendipity and and frank had found a niche that he wanted to publish in he really enjoyed and he had the funding to do it i think it was just perfect the circumstances were just right now had that had that uh link with uh the moore's already

happened before you got here yes okay so the Mondale Rogers book was was done that was that was in the works when I know let me think I think I copy edited the Mondale Rogers because if I'm not I believe that was one that came here or more after I got here because that's the manuscript that was placed before
He's the one, the Westex's scenes.
That's the one placed before Joe Moore because he was president of the former students that year.
That's the one, right.
That was the first one in the series.
Let me add my recollection of that to this tape.
Dr. Williams and Bob Walker were going to call on J. Harold Dunn up in Amarillo, looking for a meaningful contribution to Texas A&M.
And Mr. Dunn, something to the effect, as I recall, he said,
Everything I've got is in cattle oil and cotton, and right now the prices on those are down, and I would really like to help with this, and particularly they showed him this manuscript.
That would interest me.
It's Texas art, and it's West Texas, but I just can't right now.
And Dr. Williams said, well, while we're in the university plane, let's stop in Midland and visit with Joe Moore, president of former students, just to say hello.
And as I recall, Joe Moore, what are you all doing?
Where have you been?
Well, we've been in Amarillo talking to J. Harold Dunn.
What about?
Well, we had this manuscript, old manuscript.
About what?
Well, the West Texas Art.
Well, let me see it.
I'm interested in West Texas Art.
And then he invited us to stay and have supper.
And he had shared it with Betty by then.
They were interested.
could spend the night.
Spend the night, and the next morning at breakfast, if I'm not mistaken, they committed a larger sum to endow the series than they'd been talking.
I left Wardlaw out of this trip.
Wardlaw and Williams, and I think Bob Walker.
But anyway, the gift, the commitment to support it was larger than the original expectation.
any other special that you thought were his pet subjects other than art?
Well, of course, the Texas regional history was always a favorite of his.
And I think he'd been interested in Texas history since he had come to Texas, I think.
And he knew the market for it.
He knew that those books would sell.
He knew he had...
the support of the Texas State Historical Association and in getting in free publicity more or less, free advertising for those books, so I think that was always a great topic for.
All right, and then at the other end of the spectrum, what were his least favorite topics?
Well, you know, I don't really know.
I know that we published a couple of books that we just sort of had to do because they were by faculty members and they were orphans, really, because we didn't have any way to market them nationally.
And Frank would sometimes complain about those that didn't really seem to have a place on our list, but he felt that we were obligated to do them.

and I won't give specifics because those authors may still be around, but there were some of those that didn't seem to be anyone's favorite, really, but the press had to support the faculty and publish them.
Right.
As you were in those early years, give some examples you can think of, recall, where you felt you had really
done it the way the boss wanted it done?
You felt good about his reaction to your work?
Well, practically every book that we did, he supported the staff.
He never, I don't remember a single time that Frank criticized any member of the staff.

for anything in any of the books i can't think of a time never never even thought about it really but i can't he just wasn't that kind of manager he would emphasize the positives but never criticize the negatives and so he was always very positive about what we published and if
Any new book that came along, he would just laud everybody for it.

Do you remember any, whether it was one that you had edited or not, do you remember any in those early years when there was a mistake in the printed, an oversight, and then the printed copy there was?
Oh, I don't remember.
I know there must have been some.
No typos, no misspellings?
No books perfect, so I can't remember specific instruments from way back then.
I usually try to forget about those things as soon as possible and not make those mistakes again.
In your early books, which one did you personally enjoy the most in the early years?

just more fun to do yeah well of course the stolen steers so you edited that one yeah and um how much editing did it take well quite a bit uh actually margaret i think margaret did the first copy editing on that yeah that was yeah that was done by margaret ingram but i uh handled the proof on it and uh worked with bill on it
It required quite a bit of copy editing, and it required a special touch because it was so close to fiction.
Well, it was fiction, really, although we labeled it as folklore.
But that kind of fiction, you don't want to over-edit.
You can't over-edit because there's so much of the author's voice in it.
over at it, then it starts to sound wooden and stilted.
So, yeah, I took a special hand to work with that.
Were there colloquial spellings, Texas pronunciation spellings?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah.
Now, what would be the guideline for that?
Well, you have to
keep the author's voice and keep the sound of the dialect, but make it readable.
There are some books of dialect that are so heavy that you can't really read them easily.
You have to work to get that dialect.
Now, if you're a native speaker, then you can read right along with it, but I'm talking about
Most of the people that you want to sell the book to, that you want to read that book, are they going to be able to read it easily?
And so we had to tone down some of the dialect in Bill Brett's books.
Did you have to kind of almost compose a reference dictionary to be sure that you were spelling this colloquial term the same way each time?
Yeah, that was part of the style sheet.
Certainly.
For a book like that, you put together a style sheet of the spellings and punctuation, and you follow that through the whole book.
And in that case, yes, the odd spellings, like do you spell O-L apostrophe or O-L-E?
I presume, would not use a linguistics professor's style of accenting and spelling.
No, not at all.
In those early years, when you got to the office and started to work at about 8 o'clock, about how long could you work without any interruption or break before you had to get up and
Take a stroll, maybe?
Oh, first couple of hours, and then we'd take a break for coffee and chit chat and get back to work.
So you could sit there?
The editors are notoriously easygoing about office hours and always have been.
And so we'd get up and visit each other in our offices and discuss particular problems of grammar or punctuation.
So it wasn't all just focusing on the papers right in front of us.
In those early years, if you came to a situation where you wanted someone else's comment, to whom did you turn?
To Margaret.
To Margaret?
Mainly.
If it was a really big problem, then we would go directly to Frank.
But if it was a matter of style or punctuation, spelling, that kind of thing,
And I couldn't resolve it with my references.
And Margaret and I would discuss it.
And sometimes she would come to me and ask me about things that were troublesome to her.
Now, to show how times have changed, I'm assuming in that era, people smoked if they wanted to in the office.
Oh, yes.
Oh, yes.
What percentage of smokers were there in the press then?
Practically everybody.
Margaret and I smoked.
Ray Gromyla smoked like a chimney.
Don Collins probably outsmoked the rest of us.
And then, of course, Frank had his cigars and pipes going all the time.
I tried to stop smoking in 77.
That was about two years after I'd come here.
And my wife had quit when our daughter,
She first found out she was pregnant with our daughter.
So she had been quit for about four years.
And I thought, I need to stop this.
I was smoking way too much.
And so I started buying cigars, too.
I'd get these little cigarillos in the little six packs or whatever.
And I'd get one of those and take it to the press.
instead of cigarettes and then portion those out through the day.
And then gradually I was able to cut down on the number that I smoked each day and finally quit that way.
But it was tough to quit because everybody was smoking up a storm.
There'd be a haze in that building so thick you couldn't cut it with a knife sometimes.
Like I, as a non-smoker, I don't remember ever thinking that that area or any other area, oh my goodness, I've got to watch out because I'm going over where everybody smokes.
It was just so common.
Oh, yeah.
Even in restaurants and so on, people smoked all the time.
We didn't pay any.
I understand it's still that way in Europe.
So my wife and I want to get back to Europe one of these days where we...
